**BANKRUPTCY RETAINER AGREEMENT**

This agreement dated and executed April 26, 2023 confirms that above named retained the undersigned attorney to prepare and file a Chapter 7 Bankruptcy Petition, under Title 11, United States Code.

In return for the attorney fee stated below, I have agreed to render legal services as follows:

a.  Analysis of your financial situation, and rendering advice in determining whether to file  bankruptcy;

b.  Preparation and filing of any petition, schedules, statement of affairs, and plan which may be required;

c.  Representation of the debtor at the meeting of creditors and hearing, and any adjourned hearings thereof.

The attorney fee stated below does not include work concerning or related to: motions, amendments to schedules and plan, annual financial statements in chapter 13 plan, adversarial proceedings, contested matters, post petition motions, removal of garnishments or wage assignments, reaffirmation agreements,  redemption procedures, post discharge matters, and Appellate proceedings.

You have agreed to pay me an *initial retainer* of  $ 1,350.00 for the purpose of assuring my availability and representation of you in the above stated matter.  Included in the *initial retainer* is the attorney minimum fee and the estimated disbursements for the costs of your action. The retainer will be credited against the overall cost of your matter and if any *retainer* balance remains upon the completion of this matter it will be refunded to you.

You agree to pay me a minimum fee of $ 1,000.00 plus *out-of pocket disbursements* to render the services stated in paragraph 2 *.* In the event that additional services are required (such as those stated in paragraph 3), the fee shall be my time at a rate of  $ 300.00 per hour plus *out-of pocket disbursements,* unless we agree otherwise *.* The minimum fee is paid from the proceeds of the initial retainer above and is not an additional payment.

You also understand and agree that minimal work will be performed on your case until the *initial retainer* has been paid in full and that the petition will not be filed with the Bankruptcy Court until said *initial retainer* has been paid in full.

*Out-of pocket disbursements* include but are not limited to costs of filing papers, postage, correspondence, photocopying, court fees, transcripts, long distance toll calls, travel, parking, court reporters, process servers, messengers, costs of accountants, appraisers, actuaries, consultants, and other expert witness fees. I will not retain accountants, appraisers, actuaries, consultants, and other expert witnesses without your prior consent. Disbursements will be itemized and deducted from the *retainer* or will be itemized and billed to you or you will be requested to pay them directly.

It is your right to be provided with copies of correspondence and any documents relating to the case, and to be kept apprised of the status of the case, however, the above fees apply.

It is your right to cancel my representation at anytime, but  if you should decide to discontinue my services in this matter prior to its resolution, or if the attorney-client relationship is terminated for non-payment, then you shall be liable for the minimum fee plus my time computed at the rate of  $ 300.00 per hour plus *out-of pocket disbursements* .

In addition, If you fail to bring the required documents to the meeting of creditors (341 meeting) as set for in the document list I sent you, and we are sent away by the trustee, you agree to pay me an additional $150.00 for my time to re-appear for the meeting.

I reserve the right to terminate the attorney-client relationship for non-payment of attorney fees or disbursements as contemplated by this agreement if payment is not made within10 days of my request for such payment. I may withdraw as your attorney upon written notice to you by mail at your above address without relieving you of any obligations for my services and disbursements to the time of my withdrawal. Bills not paid within 30 days will accrue interest at the rate of 9% annual percentage rate compounded daily from the date of the request for payment to the date of the payment.

\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_

Stephen K. Underwood, Esq.

1395 Union Road

West Seneca, NY

716-656-7676

I (we) have read and understand the above agreement and accept all of its terms, and understand that I must complete Credit Counseling from an approved counselor before the petition my be filed (11 USC §109(h)).

## AGREEMENT OF SETTLEMENT AND STIPULA  TIOl\

THIS  AGREEMENT is  made the \~~ day of J 6.1\..V"'()-, 20 ~ .  by  and between, SHANNON M FISHER (hereinafter referred to as "wife"), and JON JERRY FISHER, JR. (hereinafter referred to  as  "husband").

## WITNESSETH

WHEREAS. the pa1iies were  married on the  8th day of January, 2005, by justice of the peace, in  Marathon. County of Monroe, State of FL; and

WHEREAS. There are two (2) children born of  this marriage, to wit: Coleton Bernard Fisher.

DOB  June 20, 2006,  and Evelyn Kay Fisher, DOB  October 8. 2007;  and

WHEREAS, will: currently cams ninety-three thousand dollars ($93,000.00) per year from employment at SUNY University at  Buffalo, and  earns  total  annual  income  from  all  sources  of ninety-three thousand dollars and no cents ($93,000.00); and

WHEREAS. husband currently earns seventy-two thousand dollars (S72.000.00) per year from employment at Eaton . and earns total annual income from al  sources of  seventy-two thousand I

Index No.:  817112/2024

AGREEMENT OF SETTLEMENT AND STIPULATION

ACTIO:\f  FOR DIVORCE

dollars and no cents ($72,000.00); and

WHEREAS, after negotiations the paiiies have arrived at a stipulation which resolves all of the outstanding issues of  this marriage; and

NOW, THEREFORE, in  consideration of  the premises and mutual covenants, promises and agreements hereinafter contained. the parties hereby agree as  follows:

## APPLlCABLE  LAW

Each  of the  pa1iies  acknowledge  regarding  the  preparation  of the  within  Agreement  of Settlement  and  Stipulation  that  said  Agreement  shall  be  construed  pursuant  to  the  terms  and conditions of  Section 236-B. 237, et.seq. , of  the New York State Domestic Relations Law.

## MAI~TENANCE

With  regard  to  maintenance.  each  party  acknowledges  to  the  other that  they  have  been advised  by  their  respective  attorneys  or  have  the  opportunity  to  consult  with  an  attorney  and specifically acknowledge that they have considered the ft)llowing in determining the necessity, non› nccessity and/or appropriate level of  maintenance:

- I) The post-divorce maintenance formula. pursuant to DRL 236-8(6);
- 2) The factors the Court would consider that may warrant a deviation from  the  post-divorce maintenance formula, specifically:
- (a)  the  age and health of  the parties;
- (b)  the  present  or  future  earning  capacity  of the  parties.  including  a  history  of limited participation in  the workforce;
- (c) the  need of  one party to incur education or training expenses;
- (d) the tem1ination ofa child support award before the termination of  the maintenance award

when the calculation of maintenance was based  upon child support being awarded which resulted in a maintenance award lower than it would have been had child support not been awarded;

- (e) the wasteful dissipation of marital property, including tTansfers or encumbrances made in  contemplation of  a matrimonial action without fair consideration;
- (f) the  existence  and  duration  of a  pre-marital joint  household  or  a  pre-divorce separate household;
- (g)  acts  by  one  party  against  another that  have  inhibited  or continue  to  inhibit  a  party's earning capacity or ability to obtain meaningful employment. Such acts include but are not limited to acts of  domestic violence as provided in section four hundred fifty-nine-a of the social services law;
- (h) the availability and cost of medical  insurance for the parties;
- (i)  the  care  of children  or  stepchildren.  disabled  adult  children  or  stepchildren,  elderly parents or in-Jaws provided during the marriage that inhibits a party's earning capacity:
- U) the tax  consequences to each party;
- (k) the standard of living of  the parties established during the marriage;
- (I) the reduced or lost earning capacity of  the payee as a result of  having forgone or delayed education, training, employment or career opportunities during the marriage:,
- (m) the equitable distribution of  marital property and the income or imputed income on the assets so distributed:
- (n)  the  contributions  and  services  of the  payee  as  a  spouse,  parent.  wage  earner  and homemaker and to the career or career potential of the other party: and

(o) any other factor which the court shalt expressly find  to  be just and proper.

After careful consideration of the maintenance formula, and the factors that may warrant a deviation  from  the  formula,  the  paiiies  have  agreed  that  neither  party  is  seeking  an  award  of maintenance, and the parties arc self-supporting. and capabk of  remaining so. and there Core neither party shall be required to pay maintenance.

I may be entitled to purchase health insurance on my own through a COBRA option, if  available; otherwise l may be required to secure my own health insurance.

<!-- image -->

## CUSTODY, VISITATION, A~D CHILD SUPPORT

With regard to custody. visitation and child support, each party acknowledges to the other that they have been advised by their respective attorneys or have the opportunity to consult with an

attorney  and  specifically  acknowledge  that  they  have  considered  the  following  guidelines  111 determining the appropriate amounts of  child suppo1i:

- a) The financial  resources of the custodial and  non-custodial  parent and those of the children;
- b) The physical and emotional health of  the children and their educational or vocational aptitudes;
- c) The  standard  of living  the  child  would  have  enjoyed  had  the  marriage  not  been dissolved;
- d) The tax consequences to  the parties;
- e) The non-monetary contributions that the parents will make toward the care and well› being of the children;
- f) The educational needs of  either parent.

After careful consideration of  the child support guidelines, the parties have agreed as follows regarding custody, visitation and child support:

## Custody

The husband and wife shall have joint legal custody of the one minor child, Evelyn Kay Fi sher, and the wife shall be the p1-irnary  1 -e s idcntiul und cu,,todial  purcnt of the child.

The agreement by the  parties  regarding custody of the children shall not be construed to operate as consent of  a party to the adoption of  the children by or the sulTendcr of  the children to any other person, nor shall such relinquishment confer upon any party any authority, in  case of  death. illness or inability to supervise the children to appoint a guardian for the children to the exclusion of the other party. If a  party shall be living at the time of the other party's death. he or she shall be

entitled to assume full  and complete custody of the children.

Notwithstanding the possible remarriage of  the w · ife, the children shall continue to be known under the husband's surname. The children shall not, for any purpose, or for any reason, assume or use the name of any subsequent husband of the wi f'e.

The paiiies agree that such other, fw1her and additional custodial arrangements pertaining to the children stemming from special events and circumstances of  the parties and the children,  and as the children get older.  shall  be by mutual agreement and consent of  both parties.  In  the event the  parties  cannot  agree  in  this  regard,  the  matter  shall  be  resolved  by  a  Court  of competent jurisdiction.

The pai1ies agree to consult vvith  each other regarding the children's education, religious training, selections of  physicians, dentists and other professionals, health, welfare, morals and other matters of similar importance affecting the children. Neither pa11y  shall  do anything overtly or cove11ly which  shall  dissuade  the  children  from  developing  and  continuing  to  develop  normal  love  and affection for a parent.

Each of the parties shall  at all times notify the other of any changes of residence whether permanent or temporary of the children, including the exact address and telephone number where the other party may communicate with the children.

Each of  the patties agrees that the children shall not be removed on a permanent basis from the County of  Eric and the State ofNcw York without the express written consent of  the other party. The said express \vritten consent shall be executed with the same formality as this agreement, or by order of the  Supreme Court of the County of Erie and  State of New York which order shall  be granted only upon twenty (20) days written notice to the other party.

## Visitation

The husband shall have reasonable visitation with rhe one minor child, as agreed to by the parties. and upon reasonable notice to the wi fc.

## Child Support

Each of  the parties acknowledges and recognizes that their agreement as to child support is governed by the terms of the Child Support Standards Act (CSSA) set forth in  Section 240 of the Domestic Relations Law of the State of New York, and  have been advised of  it's provisions.

The husband shall pay Child Support to the wife for the two (2) children, in the amount of no dollars and  no cents ($0.00). weekly,  until the occurrence of an  emancipating event. For the purposes of  this agreement, an emancipation event shall be deemed to have occurred on the earliest happening of  any of  the following:

- a) Reaching the age of 21 years;
- b) Marriage;
- c) Permanent residence away from the residence of the wife. hovvever, residence at a boarding school, camp or college is not deemed to be a permanent residence away from  the wife;
- d) Death;
- e) Full time entry into the military service of the Untied States;
- f) Engaging in  full-time  employment which  shall  be defined as  that employment in excess of  35 hours per week. However, engaging by the child in partial employment or working during any vacations or recess periods from school shall not be deemed an emancipation event.

The parties  have received a copy of  the CSSA Chart promulgated by the Commissioner of Social Services pursuant to subdivision two of  section one hundred eleven-I of  the Social Services Law .

Each or the  parties  acknowledges and recognizes  that  the  basic child  support  obligation provided  for in  the  provisions of the CSSA  would presumptively rcsu It  in  the correct amount of child support to be awarded, however. the parties wish to enter into an agreement that deviates from the basic child support obligation.

Each of the parties acknowledges and understands that the provisions of the CSSA would require  the  child  suppo11  payment  to  be  three  hundred  nineteen  dollars  and  sixty-seven  cents ($3 l 9.67),weekly,  but the parties have agreed otherwise for the  following reasons:

- a) The husband is expected to spend considerable time with the children.
- b) The husband is paying for half of the children's medical insurance.
- c) The husband is paying half of the children's expenses.

## In addition, the parties agree as follows :

The wife shall provide medical and hospital  insurance for the two (2) children on NYSHTP so  long  as  it  is  available,  and  the  husband  will  reimburse  the  wife  half of the  difference  in  the premium between a single plan and family plan.  Each party shall be responsible for  paying half of all  uninsured  medical , dental. drug,  optical, orthodontic. counseling and  health  related  expenses incurred on behalf of the children.

Both  patiies agree to  pay half of the children's expenses as  agreed and arranged until  the children reach the age of  21. including but not limited to their respective cell phones, car insurance. and  other  necessary  expenses,  and  both  parents  agree  to  assist  the  children  equally  with  their

educational expenses and loans.

The parties also agree that each party has a right to seek a modification of  the child support agreement herein upon a showing of  (l) a substantial change in circumstances: or (11) that three years have passed since this  agreement was  made,  last  modified, or adjusted;  or (III) there has been a change in either party's  gross income by fifteen percent or more since this agreement was made, last modified, or adjusted, UNLESS the parties have specifically opted out of  subparagraph (II), or (lll) of  this paragraph as set forth and agreed as follows: The parties agree that they will opt out of  both part IT  and  Tl 1  of  the  modification provisions.

## MARITAL PROPERTY

Each of  the pa11ies acknowledge and agrees with each other that they have been advised by their attorneys or have the opportunity to consult with an attorney, that pursuant to the applicable Jaws of  the Stare of  New York. all of  the marital property. as defined by DRL 236-B(c). accumulated by the parties during the course of their marriage, regardless of the  form  in which title is held.  is subject to equitable distribution. Each party fwther acknowledges that the distributive award shall be the payment from one spouse to the other to supplement. facilitate or effectuate the division or distribution of their marital  property.

Each party acknowledges and understands that the following property shall be specifically excluded from marital property.

- I . Property acquired before the marriage or property acquired by bequest, devise, or descent,  or gift from a pm1y other than the spouse.
- 2. Compensation for personal  injuries:

- 3. Property  acquired  in  exchange  for  or the  increase  in  value  of separate  property, except  to  the  extent  that  such  appreciation  is  due  in  pati  to  the  contributions  or efforts of  the other spouse.
- 4. Property described as separate property by written agreement of  the parties pursuant to DRL 236-8(3).
- 5. Veteran's benefits exempt from attachment, levy or seizure pursuant to the laws of the  United  States,  except  when  a  Veteran  has  waived  a  po1iion  of his  military retirement pay in order lo receive Veteran's compensations.

## DISTRJBUTIO~ OF PROPERTY

Each of the  parties acknowledge and agree,  that after reviewing all  of their separate and marital property, that they agree as follows:

- a) That each party shall retain as his or her sole and separate propc1ty those items of property now in  his or her possession and/or name, including but not limited to his or  her  real  estate,  business  interests,  automobiles,  financial  accounts,  and  any pension rights, 40 l k's  and/or other retirement accounts that either party may possess. EXCEPT:
- i) That  the  husband  shall  transfer  his  interest  in the  marital  residence commonly known as 242 Carriage  Park,  West Seneca, NY,  via  quitclaim deed,  to  the  wi fc.  at  such  time  as  the  wife  refinances  and/or assumes  the mortgage  on  the  marital  residence.  and  pays  the  husband  seventy-nine thousand, seven-hundred  and  fifty dollars ($79.750.00). This  amount represents the husband's  half  share of  the equity in the marital residence.  The

wife shall be responsible for paying all costs associated with the transfer of husband's  interest.  The  wife  shall  be responsible  for  paying  all  of the expenses  associated  with  home  ownership including  but  not  limited  to paying the mortgage, taxes,  and insurance, and  shall  indemnify,  and  hold husband harmless for said expenses, unless the husband is still residing at the marital residence, in  that case, the expenses shall be split equally.

ii)  The husband agrees to  transfer his interest in  the 2016 Chevy lmpala to Evelyn  Fisher,  and transfer his interest in  the  20 I  0 Ford  Fusion  to Coleton Fisher.

iii)  Each party will  retain as their sole and separate property fifty percent of the  Joint  savings  account,  after  the  wife  first  receives  $3500.00, and  the husband  first  receives S2500.00.

iv) The pa1iics agree to divide the household prope1iy as agreed and arranged.

## MARlT AL DEBTS

Except  as  othern·ise  provided  in  this  agreement,  the  parties  represent  that  neither  has incurred, and will not at any time in the future incur, any debt charge or liability for which the other is  now or may become liable. Each party further agrees at all  times. to indemnify the other party from,  and  hold  that  party  free  and  harmless  against,  any  and  all  debts,  charges.  contracts  and liabilities contracted by such party.  In the event that either pariy violates this provision and the other is thereby obligated to make payment to others. the party making such payment shall have the right to deduct such amount from the next amount or amounts payable to the other under any provisions of  this Agreement.  The paiiy intending to so deduct must afford the other party a minimum \Vrittcn

notice of  ten days prior to  taking the deduction as provided for herein above.

The parties also agree as follows:

- a) That  each  pa1iy  shall  be  responsible  for  those  debts  and  obligations  in  his  or her respective name.  EXCEPT:
- i) In  the event that wife's student loans are not forgiven in July of  2025, the husband agrees to pay the wife l\venty-five percent of  the monthly payment on  her student loans until such time as  the  loans arc forgiven.

## T  A.X  CONSEQUENCES

The parties understand that there  is  no  longer a value to the tax dependency exemption for the children, and that only a tax credit is available until each child reaches age seventeen ( 17).  That the parties agree that the wife shall be entitled to claim the children for the tax credit in all tax years, on  federal  and state income tax returns.  In the event that the tax dependency is reinstated, the wife shall receive the dependent income tax deduction for each chi Id as set fo1th above, on all federal and state  income tax returns.

## COUNSEL FEES

In regards to counsel fees,  the parties agree as  follows: That each party shall be responsible for  their own attorney's fees and  disbursements.

## INCORPORATION

lf  a divorce is  granted at anytime to  either party against the other in  this state or any other state having jurisdiction over the parties, it  is  agreed that:

- l. Neither of the  parties shall cause or request  that any provision be inserted in  the final judgment which  is inconsistent with any of the within  Agreement.
- 2. The terms and provisions of this Agreement shall  be offered into evidence and shall

be incorporated in  and become pa11 of. any such final  Judgement or Decree of such divorce action, but shall  not merge therein.

- 3. That all provision's  of  this Agreement shall survive as a result of  such incorporation into said Decree of Divorce and shall continue to be binding upon the parties.

## CHANGE OR :\10DIFICATIOJ\

That no  provision of  this  Agreement be discharged or terminated  in  whole or in  part, except by an agreement in  writing signed by the party against whom the change, modification or discharge is claimed or sought to be enforced, or by his agent authorized in  writing and signed by the said pa11y to make such change, modification, discharge or termination.

## WARRANTIES AND REPRESE~TA TIONS

That  this  Agreement  constitutes  the  entire  understanding  of the  pa11ies. There  are  no representations, promises. wanantics, covenants or undertakings other than those expressly set forth herein.

## COU~TERPARTS

This Agreement may be executed by the separate signatures and acknowledgments of the parties  hereto  on  counterpart  copies  hereof and  shall  become  effective  when  counterparts  so executed and acknowledged have been exchanged by the parties.

## RIGHT OF ELECTION

Subject to the provisions of  this Agreement, each of  the pa11ies may, in any way, dispose of his or her property of whatever nature, real or personal , and each of the parties hereto,  for himself or herself, and for his or her heirs, legal representative, executors, administrators and assigns, hereby waives any right of election \vhich he or she may have or hereafter acquire regarding the estate of the other. or to take against the Last \Viii and Testament of  the other, whether heretofore or hereafter

executed, as provided by Article V of  the Estates, Powers and Trust Law of  the State of  New York, or as may now or thereinafter be provided for in any law of  the State of  New York. or any other state of territory of the United States,  or any foreign  country.  and renounces and releases  all  interest, rights or claims or right of  dower or curtesy or otherwise, that he or she now has or might otherwise have against the other, or the prope1iy of  whatever nature, real or personal, or the other under of  by virtue of the law of  any state, territory or county, and each will, at the request of  the other,  or his or her legal representatives, executors, administrators and assigns, execute, acknowledge and deliver any and all  deeds, releases or any other instruments necessary to bar, release or extinguish such interest  rights  and  claims,  or which  may be necessary  to  effectuate  any of the provision  of this Agreement.  Each of  the parties renounces and relinquishes any and all claims and rights that he or she may have or hereafter acquire to act as executor or administrator of the other party's estate.

## INTERPRET ATlON

All matters affecting the interpretation of  this Agreement and the rights of  the parties herein shall be governed by the laws of  the State of New York.

## INVALIDITY AND UNENFORCEABILITY

In  the event that any paragraph or portion of  any paragraph of  this Agreement shall be held invalid  or unenforceable for  any reason,  it  shall  not  in  any  way  invalidate,  affect  or impair the remaining paragraphs of this Agreement, it being the intention of the parties that this Agreement shall be binding upon and enforced against both parties to the extent permitted by law.

## RELEASE Al\D DISCHARGE

Subject to  the provisions of this agreement, each party has remised, released and forever discharged and by these presence docs for  himself  and herself, and  his or  her heirs, legal

representatives. executors, administrators and assigns. remise and release and forever discharge the other of  and from all cause or causes of  action, claims. rights or demands, whatsoever, in  law or in equity, which he or she ever had or now has against the other. except any or all causes of  action  for divorce based on past. present or future  grounds. and any or all  causes of action arising from the failure of  either patty to  perform in full  his or her obligation under this Agreement.

## NECESSARY INSTRUMENTS

Each of  the parties hereto agrees further at any time and from time to time to make. execute and deliver all instruments necessary to effectuate the provisions of this Agreement.

## W AIYER OF BREACH

Each  of the  parties  hereto  agrees  further  that  no  waiver  of any  breach  or default thereunder shall be deemed to waiver of any subsequent breach or default of the same or similar nature.

## COMPLETE lJNDERST  ANDING

This  Agreement  constitutes  the  complete  understanding  of the  parties. There  are  no representations  promises  or  wananties  other  than  those  expressly  set  fotth  herein  and  those incorporated by reference.  The parties agree that  no oral statements or prior matters or otherwise extrinsic to  this Agreement shall  have any force  or  effect. The  parties  are  not  relying  upon any representations other than those expressly set forth  herein, which include good faith  financial disclosures by each.

The husband acknowledges that he has entered into this Agreement without coercion of  any kind from any source whatsoever and that he clearly understands and consents to any provisions herein.  That he believes this Agreement to be fair, just and reasonable.

The wife acknowledges that she has entered into this Agreement without coercion of any

kind  from  any source whatsoever and that she clearly understands and consent to any provisions herein. That she believes this Agreement to be fair, just and reasonable.

Except as otherwise stated herein, all  the provision of this Agreement shall  be binding upon the respective heirs, next of  kin, executors and administrators of  the parties.

## REPRESENTATION Al\D DISCLOSURE

The parties acknowledge that each has sought and obtained independent legal  advice from counsel  of his  or  her  own  selection,  or  had  the  opportunity  to  do  so. Each  of the  parties acknowledge  that  he  or  she  has  therefore  been  fully  informed  of his  or  her  legal  rights  and obligations with respect to the subject matter of  this Agreement, has had an opportunity to read the Agreement and discuss  its various  provisions  with an  attorney of his  or her choosing, has  been satisfied with the extent to which financial disclosure has been provided, and waives any right he or she may have to further financial disclosure or to complain in the future with respect to the extent or nature of  disclosure, either against his or her attorney or against the other spouse.

## Explanation of Bankruptcy Discharge in a Chapter 7 Case

This order does not close or dismiss the case, and it does not determine how much money, if any, the trustee will pay creditors.

This order does not prevent debtors from paying any debt voluntarily or from paying reaffirmed debts according to the reaffirmation agreement. 11 U.S.C. § 524(c), (f).

## Creditors cannot collect discharged debts

This order means that no one may make any attempt to collect a discharged debt from the debtors personally. For example, creditors cannot sue, garnish wages, assert a deficiency, or otherwise try to collect from the debtors personally on discharged debts. Creditors cannot contact the debtors by mail, phone, or otherwise in any attempt to collect the debt personally. Creditors who violate this order can be required to pay debtors damages and attorney's fees.

However, a creditor with a lien may enforce a claim against the debtors' property subject to that lien unless the lien was avoided or eliminated. For example, a creditor may have the right to foreclose a home mortgage or repossess an automobile.

## Most debts are discharged

Most debts are covered by the discharge, but not all. Generally, a discharge removes the debtors' personal liability for debts owed before the debtors' bankruptcy case was filed.

Also, if this case began under a different chapter of the Bankruptcy Code and was later converted to chapter 7, debts owed before the conversion are discharged.

In a case involving community property: Special rules protect certain community property owned by the debtor's spouse, even if that spouse did not file a bankruptcy case.

For more information, see page 2 >

page 1

## Some debts are not discharged

Examples of debts that are not discharged are:

- debts that are domestic support obligations; ♦
- debts for most student loans; ♦
- debts for most taxes; ♦
- debts that the bankruptcy court has decided or will decide are not discharged in this bankruptcy case; ♦
- debts for most fines, penalties, f o r f e i t u r e s ,   o r   c r i m i n a l   r e s t i t u t i o n obligations; ♦
- some debts which the debtors did not properly list; ♦
- debts for certain types of loans owed to pension, profit sharing, stock bonus, or retirement plans; and ♦
- debts for death or personal injury caused by operating a vehicle while intoxicated. ♦

Official Form 318

Order of Discharge

Also, debts covered by a valid reaffirmation agreement are not discharged.

I n addition, this discharge does not stop creditors from collecting from anyone else who is also liable on the debt, such as an insurance company or a person who cosigned or guaranteed a loan.

This information is only a general summary of the bankruptcy discharge; some exceptions exist. Because the law is complicated, you should consult an attorney to determine the exact effect of the discharge in this case.

JUDGMENT OF DIVORCE

ENTERED UPON REFEREE'S REPORT

\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_

At a Trial Term of the Supreme Court of the State of New York held in the County of    Erie, Buffalo, New York on the

\_\_\_\_\_day of \_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_ 20\_\_\_\_.

EACH PARTY HAS A RIGHT TO SEEK A MODIFICATION OF THE CHILD SUPPORT ORDER UPON A SHOWING OF: (I) A SUBSTANTIAL CHANGE IN CIRCUMSTANCES; OR (II)  THAT  THREE  YEARS  HAVE  PASSED  SINCE  THE  ORDER  WAS  ENTERED,  LAST MODIFIED OR ADJUSTED; OR (III) THERE HAS BEEN A CHANGE IN EITHER PARTY'S GROSS INCOME BY FIFTEEN PERCENT OR MORE SINCE THE ORDER WAS ENTERED, LAST MODIFIED, OR ADJUSTED; HOWEVER, IF THE PARTIES HAVE SPECIFICALLY OPTED OUT OF SUBPARAGRAPH (II) OR (III) OF THIS PARAGRAPH IN A VALIDLY EXECUTED AGREEMENT OR STIPULATION, THEN THAT BASIS TO SEEK MODIFICATION DOES NOT APPLY.

The above entitled action having been brought on by the Plaintiff for a Judgement of Divorce against the Defendant dissolving the marriage heretofore existing between the parties upon the grounds of DRL §170(7) Relationship Irretrievably Broken, and the Defendant having been duly and personally served with the Summons With Notice bearing a notation 'Action for Divorce' , thereon within the State of  New York, after the enactment of the New York State Equitable Distribution Law, and the Defendant having appeared and waived  the right to answer, and consented to a Default Judgement, and the parties having settled the ancillary issues by written stipulation, and the Plaintiff having applied to this Court at a term thereof held in and for the County of Erie, for a Judgement of Absolute Divorce for the relief demanded in the Verified Complaint, and the Plaintiff, by Attorney STEPHEN K. UNDERWOOD, ESQ., presenting the Verified Complaint, written proof of the service of the Summons upon the Defendant, Affidavit of Non-Military Service, Affidavit of Regularity, and the matter having been referred to a Matrimonial  Referee  and  the  Referee  having  submitted  a  report  containing  Findings  of  Fact  and Conclusions of Law, and deciding among other things that the Plaintiff was entitled to a Judgement of Divorce against the Defendant dissolving the marriage heretofore existing between the parties hereto, pursuant to the statute, on the grounds of DRL §170(7) Relationship Irretrievably Broken.

NOW, on the motion of STEPHEN K. UNDERWOOD, ESQ., attorney for Plaintiff, it is hereby ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that the Referee's Report is confirmed; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that the Plaintiff, SHANNON M FISHER, is hereby granted a Judgement of Divorce against the Defendant, JON JERRY FISHER, JR., dissolving the marriage relationship heretofore existing between the Plaintiff and Defendant on the grounds of DRL §170(7) Relationship Irretrievably Broken; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that the parties shall have joint legal custody of the one minor child, Evelyn Kay Fisher, DOB  October 8, 2007, and the Plaintiff shall be the primary residential and custodial parent of the child; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that the Defendant shall pay Child Support to Plaintiff for the two (2) children, in the amount of no dollars and no cents ($0.00), weekly; and that the parties have entered into an agreement that deviates from the basic child support obligation, and that the aforesaid obligation is not unjust or inappropriate for the reasons set forth in the agreement; specifically, that:

- a) The husband is expected to spend considerable time with the children;
- b) The husband is paying for half of the children's medical insurance;
- c) The husband is paying half of the children's expenses;

and it is further

ORDERED,  ADJUDGED  AND  DECREED, that  the  Defendant  shall  receive  reasonable visitation with the one minor child, as agreed to by the parties, and upon reasonable notice to the Plaintiff; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that the Agreement of Settlement and Stipulation entered into between the parties on the 18th day of January, 2025, a copy of which is on file with this Court and incorporated herein by reference, shall survive and shall not be merged into this judgment, and the  parties  are  hereby  directed  to  comply  with  all  legally  enforceable  terms  and  conditions  of  said agreement as if such terms and conditions were set forth in their entirety herein, and the terms were fair and reasonable at the time of the making and the terms are not now unconscionable at the time of the entry of final Judgment herein; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED , that the Supreme Court shall retain jurisdiction to hear any applications to enforce the provisions of said Agreement of Settlement and Stipulation, or to enforce or modify the provisions of this judgment, provided the court retains jurisdiction of the matter concurrently with the Family Court for the purpose of specifically enforcing, such of the provisions of said Agreement of Settlement and Stipulation, as are capable of specific enforcement, to the extent permitted by law, and of modifying such judgment with respect to maintenance, support, custody or visitation to the extent permitted by law, or both; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED , that any applications brought in Supreme Court to enforce the provisions of said Agreement of Settlement and Stipulation, or to enforce or modify the provisions of this judgment shall be brought in a County wherein one of the parties resides, provided that if there are minor children of the marriage, such applications shall be brought in a county wherein one of the parties or the child or children reside, except, in the discretion of the judge, for good cause. Good cause applications shall be made by motion or order to show cause. Where the address of either party and any child or children is unknown and not a matter of public record, or is subject to an existing confidentiality order pursuant to DRL § 254 or FCA § 154-b, such applications may be brought in the county where the judgment was entered; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that the parties have agreed and acknowledged in their agreement that they both fully understand that upon the entry of the Judgment of Divorce that he or she may no longer be allowed to receive health insurance coverage under his or her former spouses's health insurance plan and may be entitled to purchase health insurance on his or her own through a COBRA option, if available; and otherwise may be required to secure his or her own health insurance; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that  the  Plaintiff  shall  provide medical and hospital insurance for the two (2) children on NYSHIP so long as it is available, and the Defendant will reimburse the Plaintiff half of the difference in the premium between a single plan and family plan.  Each party shall be responsible for paying half of all uninsured medical, dental, drug, optical, orthodontic, counseling and health related expenses incurred on behalf of the children; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that both parties shall pay half of the children's expenses as agreed and arranged until the children reach the age of 21, including but not limited to their respective cell phones, car insurance, and other necessary expenses, and both parents agree to assist the children equally with their educational expenses and loans; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that  the Plaintiff shall be entitled to claim the children for the tax credit in all tax years, on federal and state income tax returns. In the event that the tax dependency is reinstated, the Plaintiff shall receive the dependent income tax deduction for each child as set forth above, on all federal and state income tax returns; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that the Plaintiff shall have the right to resume use of her maiden name or former surname, Bartella, should she so desire; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that each party shall retain as his or her sole and separate property those items of property now in his or her possession and/or name, including but not limited to his or her real estate, business interests, automobiles, financial accounts, and any pension rights, 401k's and/or other retirement accounts that either party may possess, EXCEPT:

i) That the Defendant shall transfer his interest in the marital residence commonly known as 242 Carriage Park, West Seneca, NY, via quitclaim deed, to the Plaintiff, at such time as the Plaintiff refinances and/or assumes the mortgage on the marital residence, and pays the Defendant seventy-nine thousand, seven-hundred and fifty dollars ($79,750.00). This amount represents the Defendant's half share of the equity in the marital residence.  The Plaintiff shall be responsible for paying all costs associated with the transfer of Defendant's interest. The Plaintiff shall be  responsible for paying all of the expenses associated with home ownership  including but not limited to paying the mortgage, taxes, and  insurance, and shall indemnify, and hold Defendant harmless for said expenses, unless the Defendant is still residing at the marital residence, in that case, the expenses shall be split equally.

ii) The Defendant agrees to transfer his interest in the 2016 Chevy Impala to Evelyn Fisher, and transfer his interest in the 2010 Ford Fusion to Coleton Fisher.

iii)  Each party will retain as their sole and separate property fifty percent of the Joint savings account, after the Plaintiff first receives $3500.00, and the Defendant first receives $2500.00.

iv) The parties agree to divide the household property as agreed and arranged; and it is further

ORDERED,  ADJUDGED  AND  DECREED , that  pursuant  to  the  parties' Agreement  of Settlement and Stipulation, all parties shall duly execute all documents necessary to formally transfer title to real estate or co-op shares, if applicable, on the terms set forth in the parties' Agreement of Settlement and Stipulation, including without limitation, an appropriate deed or other conveyance of title, and all other forms necessary to record such deed or other title documents (including the satisfaction or refinance of any mortgage if necessary) as set forth in said agreement, and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that each party shall be responsible for those debts and obligations in his or her respective name, EXCEPT:

i)  In the event that Plaintiff's student loans are not forgiven in July of 2025, the Defendant agrees to pay the Plaintiff twenty-five percent of the monthly payment on her student loans until such time as the loans are forgiven; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that the parties are self-supporting and capable of remaining so, and therefore neither party shall be required to pay maintenance; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED , the requirements of DRL § 240 1 (a) including the Records Checking Requirements in DRL § 240 1 (a-1) have been satisfied; and it is further

ORDERED, ADJUDGED AND DECREED, that each party shall be responsible for his or her respective attorney's fees and disbursements.

The bankruptcy forms use you and Debtor 1 to refer to a debtor filing alone. A married couple may file a bankruptcy case together-called a joint case -and in joint cases, these forms use you to ask for information from both debtors. For example, if a form asks, 'Do you own a car,' the answer would be yes if either debtor owns a car. When information is needed about the spouses separately, the form uses Debtor 1 and Debtor 2 to distinguish between them. ## The types of bankruptcy that are available to individuals

Individuals who meet the qualifications may file under one of four different chapters of the Bankruptcy Code:

-  Chapter 7  -  Liquidation

-  Chapter 11  -  Reorganization

- 

Chapter 12  -  Voluntary repayment plan for family farmers or fishermen

-  Chapter 13  -  Voluntary repayment plan for individuals with regular income

You should have an attorney review your decision to file for bankruptcy and the choice of chapter.

Chapter 7 is for individuals who have financial difficulty preventing them from paying their debts and who are willing to allow their nonexempt property to be used to pay their creditors. The primary purpose of filing under chapter 7 is to have your debts discharged. The bankruptcy discharge relieves you after bankruptcy from having to pay many of your pre-bankruptcy debts. Exceptions exist for particular debts, and liens on property may still be enforced after discharge. For example, a creditor may have the right to foreclose a home mortgage or repossess an automobile.

However, if the court finds that you have committed certain kinds of improper conduct described in the Bankruptcy Code, the court may deny your discharge.

You should know that even if you file chapter 7 and you receive a discharge, some debts are not discharged under the law.

Therefore, you may still be responsible to pay:

-  most taxes;
-  most student loans;
-  domestic support and property settlement obligations;

-  most fines, penalties, forfeitures, and criminal restitution obligations; and
-  certain debts that are not listed in your bankruptcy papers.

You may also be required to pay debts arising from:

-  fraud or theft;
-  fraud or defalcation while acting in breach of fiduciary capacity;
-  intentional injuries that you inflicted; and
-  death or personal injury caused by operating a motor vehicle, vessel, or aircraft while intoxicated from alcohol or drugs.

If your debts are primarily consumer debts, the court can dismiss your chapter 7 case if it finds that you have enough income to repay creditors a certain amount. You must file Chapter 7 Statement of Your Current Monthly Income (Official Form 122A-1) if you are an individual filing for bankruptcy under chapter 7. This form will determine your current monthly income and compare whether your income is more than the median income that applies in your state.

If your income is not above the median for your state, you will not have to complete the other chapter 7 form, the Chapter 7 Means Test Calculation (Official Form 122A-2).

If your income is above the median for your state, you must file a second form -the Chapter  7 Means Test Calculation (Official Form 122A-2). The calculations on the formsometimes called the Means Test -deduct from your income living expenses and payments on certain debts to determine any amount available to pay unsecured creditors. If your income is more than the median income for your state of residence and family size, depending on the results of the Means Test , the U.S. trustee, bankruptcy administrator, or creditors can file a motion to dismiss your case under § 707(b) of the Bankruptcy Code. If a motion is filed, the court will decide if your case should be dismissed. To avoid dismissal, you may choose to proceed under another chapter of the Bankruptcy Code.

If you are an individual filing for chapter 7 bankruptcy, the trustee may sell your property to pay your debts, subject to your right to exempt the property or a portion of the proceeds from the sale of the property. The property, and the proceeds from property that your bankruptcy trustee sells or liquidates that you are entitled to, is called exempt property . Exemptions may enable you to keep your home, a car, clothing, and household items or to receive some of the proceeds if the property is sold.

Exemptions are not automatic. To exempt property, you must list it on Schedule C: The Property You Claim as Exempt (Official Form 106C). If you do not list the property, the trustee may sell it and pay all of the proceeds to your creditors.

## Chapter 11: Reorganization

$1,167 filing fee

$1,717 total fee

Chapter 11 is often used for reorganizing a business, but is also available to individuals. The provisions of chapter 11 are too complicated to summarize briefly.

## Read These Important Warnings

Because bankruptcy can have serious long-term financial and legal consequences, including loss of your property, you should hire an attorney and carefully consider all of your options before you file. Only an attorney can give you legal advice about what can happen as a result of filing for bankruptcy and what your options are. If you do file for bankruptcy, an attorney can help you fill out the forms properly and protect you, your family, your home, and your possessions.

Although the law allows you to represent yourself in bankruptcy court, you should understand that many people find it difficult to represent themselves successfully. The rules are technical, and a mistake or inaction may harm you. If you file without an attorney, you are still responsible for knowing and following all of the legal requirements.

You should not file for bankruptcy if you are not eligible to file or if you do not intend to file the necessary documents.

Bankruptcy fraud is a serious crime; you could be fined and imprisoned if you commit fraud in your bankruptcy case.  Making a false statement, concealing property, or obtaining money or property by fraud in connection with a bankruptcy case can result in fines up to $250,000, or imprisonment for up to 20 years, or both. 18 U.S.C. §§ 152, 1341, 1519, and 3571.

Similar to chapter 13, chapter 12 permits family farmers and fishermen to repay their debts over a period of time using future earnings and to discharge some debts that are not paid.

## Chapter 13:  Repayment plan for individuals with regular income

$235

filing fee

+

$75 administrative fee

$310

total fee

Chapter 13 is for individuals who have regular income and would like to pay all or part of their debts in installments over a period of time and to discharge some debts that are not paid. You are eligible for chapter 13 only if your debts are not more than certain dollar amounts set forth in 11 U.S.C. § 109.

Under chapter 13, you must file with the court a plan to repay your creditors all or part of the money that you owe them, usually using your future earnings. If the court approves your plan, the court will allow you to repay your debts, as adjusted by the plan, within 3 years or 5 years, depending on your income and other factors.

After you make all the payments under your plan, many of your debts are discharged. The debts that are not discharged and that you may still be responsible to pay include:

-  domestic support obligations,
-  most student loans,
-  certain taxes,
-  debts for fraud or theft,
-  debts for fraud or defalcation while acting in a fiduciary capacity,
-  most criminal fines and restitution obligations,
-  certain debts that are not listed in your bankruptcy papers,
-  certain debts for acts that caused death or personal injury, and
-  certain long-term secured debts.

## Warning: File Your Forms on Time

Section 521(a)(1) of the Bankruptcy Code requires that you promptly file detailed information about your creditors, assets, liabilities, income, expenses and general financial condition. The court may dismiss your bankruptcy case if you do not file this information within the deadlines set by the Bankruptcy Code, the Bankruptcy Rules, and the local rules of the court.

For more information about the documents and their deadlines, go to:

http://www.uscourts.gov/bkforms/bankruptcy\_form s.html#procedure.

Bankruptcy crimes have serious consequences

-  If you knowingly and fraudulently conceal assets or make a false oath or statement under penalty of perjury-either orally or in writing-in connection with a bankruptcy case, you may be fined, imprisoned, or both.
-  All information you supply in connection with a bankruptcy case is subject to examination by the Attorney General acting through the Office of the U.S. Trustee, the Office of the U.S. Attorney, and other offices and employees of the U.S. Department of Justice.

Make sure the court has your mailing address

The bankruptcy court sends notices to the mailing address you list on Voluntary Petition for Individuals Filing for Bankruptcy (Official Form 101). To ensure that you receive information about your case, Bankruptcy Rule 4002 requires that you notify the court of any changes in your address.

A married couple may file a bankruptcy case together-called a joint case . If you file a joint case and each spouse lists the same mailing address on the bankruptcy petition, the bankruptcy court generally will mail you and your spouse one copy of each notice, unless you file a statement with the court asking that each spouse receive separate copies.

Understand which services you could receive from credit counseling agencies

The law generally requires that you receive a credit counseling briefing from an approved credit counseling agency. 11 U.S.C. § 109(h). If you are filing a joint case, both spouses must receive the briefing. With limited exceptions, you must receive it within the 180 days before you file your bankruptcy petition. This briefing is usually conducted by telephone or on the Internet.

In addition, after filing a bankruptcy case, you generally must complete a financial management instructional course before you can receive a discharge. If you are filing a joint case, both spouses must complete the course.

You can obtain the list of agencies approved to provide both the briefing and the instructional course from:

http://justice.gov/ust/eo/hapcpa/ccde/cc\_approved.html .

In Alabama and North Carolina, go to: http://www.uscourts.gov/FederalCourts/Bankruptcy/ BankruptcyResources/ApprovedCredit AndDebtCounselors.aspx .

If you do not have access to a computer, the clerk of the bankruptcy court may be able to help you obtain the list.

## ORDER FOR INTERPLEADER AND DISMISSAL OF BANKERS CONSECO LIFE INSURANCE COMPANY

Upon  the  motion  to  deposit  funds  and  dismiss  of  Bankers  Conseco  Life  Insurance Company  ('Bankers'  or  'Plaintiff'),  Plaintiff  respectfully  requests  an  Order,  pursuant  to C.P.L.R. § 1006(g), directing Bankers to pay into an interest-bearing account with the Court the proceeds  in  the  total  amount  of  $8,000.00,  plus  interest  to  date,  if  any,  which  represents  the Death  Benefit  proceeds  payable  upon  the  death  of  Debra  Warren  (the  'Policyholder')  under Whole Life Insurance Policy No. ***5818 (the 'Policy'), discharging Bankers of all liability, and dismissing with prejudice all claims against Bankers relating to the Policy and/or the Death Benefit. The Court having considered the application of counsel, and for good cause shown:

IT IS ORDERED as follows:

## INTERPLEADER WITH COURT

- 1.  That Bankers shall deposit with the Erie County Director of Finance the total amount of $8,000.00, plus applicable claim interest to date, if any, which represents the Death Benefit proceeds payable under the Policy; and

- 2.  That  the  Erie  County  Director  of  Finance  shall  deposit  the  Death  Benefit,  paid pursuant  to  this  Order  by  Bankers,  into  an  interest-bearing  account  and  maintain  the  same pending further orders of this Court; and
- 3.  That,  upon  deposit  of  the  Death  Benefit  with  the  Erie  County  Director  of  Finance, Bankers shall be, and hereby is, dismissed from the above-captioned action with prejudice and discharged from any and all liability to the Defendants Karla Warren and Kimberly Hemphill a/k/a Kimberly Garner (collectively, the "Defendants''), relating to the Policy and/or the Death Benefit, and that the Defendants shall be, and hereby are, permanently enjoined from making any further actual or implied claims, demands and causes of action, asserted or unasserted, express or implied,  foreseen  or  unforeseen,  real  or  imaginary,  suspected  or  unsuspected,  known  or unknown, liquidated or unliquidated, of any kind or nature or description whatsoever, that the Defendants, jointly or severally, ever had, presently have, may have, or claim or assert to have, or  hereinafter  have,  may  have,  or  claim  or  assert  to  have,  against  Bankers  with  respect  to  the Policy or the payment of the Death Benefit under the Policy; and
- 4.  That any and all claims against Bankers relating to the Policy and/or the Death Benefit be, and the same hereby are, dismissed with prejudice and without costs to any party; and
- 5.  That any and all claims against Bankers relating to the Policy and/or the Death Benefit shall be, and the same hereby are, dismissed with prejudice and without costs to any party.

IT  IS FURTHER ORDERED that  any  application  by  the  Defendants  to  obtain  the proceeds of the Policy and/or the Death Benefit shall be made to the Erie County Surrogate's Court.

Dated: \_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_

HON:  \_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_JSC

## STATE OF NEW YORK: SUPREME COURT COUNTY OF ERIE

\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_

## SHANNON M FISHER

Plaintiff,

-against-

JON JERRY FISHER, JR.

Index No.: 817112/2024

REFEREE'S REPORT

FINDINGS OF FACT CONCLUSIONS OF LAW

Defendant.

\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_

The above entitled action having been brought on by the Plaintiff for a Judgement of Divorce against the Defendant dissolving the marriage heretofore existing between the parties upon the grounds of DRL §170(7) Relationship Irretrievably Broken and the Defendant having been duly and personally served with the Summons With Notice bearing a notation 'Action for Divorce' , thereon within the State of New York, after the enactment of the New York State Equitable Distribution Law, and the Defendant having appeared and waived  the right to answer, and consented to a Default Judgment, and  upon reading and filing the papers submitted, and due deliberation having been had, I find and decide as follows:

## FINDINGS OF FACT

- 1)  The parties have been residents of the State of New York for a continuous period of more than two years immediately preceding the commencement of this action and continue to be residents of the state at the present time.
- 2) The parties were both over the age of eighteen (18) years at the time of the commencement of this action.
- 3) The parties were married on January 8, 2005,  by justice of the peace, in  Marathon, County of Monroe, State of FL.
- 4) Plaintiff's maiden name or former surname is: Bartella.
- 5) There are two (2) children born of this marriage, to wit: Coleton Bernard Fisher, DOB  June 20, 2006, and Evelyn Kay Fisher, DOB  October 8, 2007.
- 6) That on January 18, 2025, the parties executed an Agreement of Settlement and Stipulation  that resolves all of the outstanding issues of the marriage, and it was agreed that said agreement shall be incorporated by reference into the Judgement of Divorce, but is not to merge therewith, but shall survive.
- 7) The parties agree that the parties shall share joint legal custody of the one minor child, Evelyn Kay Fisher, and the Plaintiff shall be the primary residential and custodial parent of the child.
- 8) The Parties agree that the Defendant shall receive reasonable visitation with the one minor child, as agreed to by the parties, and upon reasonable notice to the Plaintiff.
- 9) The grounds for divorce alleged in the Verified Complaint were proved as follows:
- a)  That within the past six (6) months, and continuing on a regular basis until the commencement of this action,  the relationship of the parties has become irretrievably broken.
- b) That the parties have had frequent arguments, and engage in constant bickering.
- c) That the parties suffer from a conflict of personality, lack concern for the emotional needs of each other, and have differing interests.
- d) That the parties  harbor resentment, distrust, and  irreversible antagonistic feelings toward one another.
- e) That, as a result of the foregoing, Plaintiff has suffered from stress, and anxiety because the relationship between the parties for all intents and purposes has ended, and is no longer viable, and beyond reconciliation.
- f) That the marriage between the parties is therefore irretrievably broken, rendering  it improper for the parties to continue to cohabit.
- 10) There is no action presently pending or heretofore determined that would affect the marital status of the parties.
- 11) At the time of service of the Summons With Notice, Action for Divorce, the Defendant was not engaged in military service of the United States.
- 12) That Pursuant to Domestic Relations Law. Section 236, I find:
- a) That the marriage is of twenty (20) years, one (1) months, duration.
- b) Plaintiff currently earns ninety-three thousand dollars ($93,000.00) per year from employment at SUNY University at Buffalo, and earns total annual income from all sources of ninety-three thousand dollars and no cents ($93,000.00).
- c) Defendant currently earns seventy-two thousand dollars ($72,000.00) per year from employment at Eaton , and earns total annual income from all sources of seventy-two thousand dollars and no cents ($72,000.00).
- d)The parties are NOT seeking equitable distribution of the marital property. All of the marital property has been divided to their mutual satisfaction pursuant to their agreement, as demonstrated by the within agreement.
- e) The Parties agree that each party shall retain as his or her sole and separate property those items of property now in his or her possession and/or name, including but not limited to his or her real estate, business interests, automobiles, financial accounts, and any pension rights, 401k's and/or other retirement accounts that either party may possess, EXCEPT:
- i) That the Defendant shall transfer his interest in the marital residence commonly known as 242 Carriage Park, West Seneca, NY, via quitclaim deed, to the Plaintiff, at such time as the Plaintiff refinances and/or assumes the mortgage on the marital residence, and pays the Defendant seventy-nine thousand, seven-hundred and fifty dollars ($79,750.00). This amount represents the Defendant's half share of the equity in the marital residence.  The Plaintiff shall be responsible for paying all costs associated with the transfer of Defendant's interest. The Plaintiff shall be  responsible for paying all of the expenses associated with

home ownership  including but not limited to paying the mortgage, taxes, and  insurance, and shall indemnify, and hold Defendant harmless for said expenses, unless the Defendant is still residing at the marital residence, in that case, the expenses shall be split equally. ii) The Defendant agrees to transfer his interest in the 2016 Chevy Impala to Evelyn Fisher,

- and transfer his interest in the 2010 Ford Fusion to Coleton Fisher.
- iii)  Each party will retain as their sole and separate property fifty percent of the Joint savings account, after the Plaintiff first receives $3500.00, and the Defendant first receives $2500.00.
- iv) The parties agree to divide the household property as agreed and arranged.
- f) The Parties agree that each party shall be responsible for those debts and obligations in his or her respective name, EXCEPT:
- i)  In the event that Plaintiff's student loans are not forgiven in July of 2025, the Defendant agrees to pay the Plaintiff twenty-five percent of the monthly payment on her student loans until such time as the loans are forgiven.
- g) That the Parties agree that they are self-supporting and capable of remaining so, and that neither party shall be required to pay maintenance.
- h) The parties have agreed and acknowledged in their agreement that they both fully understand that upon the entry of the Judgment of Divorce that he or she may no longer be allowed to receive health insurance coverage under his or her former spouses's health insurance plan and may be entitled to purchase health insurance on his or her own through a COBRA option, if available; and otherwise may be required to secure his or her own health insurance.
- i) The Parties agree that each party shall be responsible for his or her own attorney's fees and disbursements.
- j) The Parties agree that Defendant shall pay Child Support to Plaintiff for the two (2) children, in

the amount of no dollars and no cents ($0.00), weekly; and that the parties have entered into an agreement that deviates from the basic child support obligation, for the reasons set forth in the agreement; specifically, that:

- i. The husband is expected to spend considerable time with the children.
- ii. The husband is paying for half of the children's medical insurance.
- iii. The husband is paying half of the children's expenses.

k) The Parties agree that the Plaintiff shall provide medical and hospital insurance for the two (2) children on NYSHIP so long as it is available, and the Defendant will reimburse the Plaintiff half of the difference in the premium between a single plan and family plan.  Each party shall be responsible for paying half of all uninsured medical, dental, drug, optical, orthodontic, counseling and health related expenses incurred on behalf of the children.

- l) Both parties agree to pay half of the children's expenses as agreed and arranged until the children reach the age of 21, including but not limited to their respective cell phones, car insurance, and other  necessary  expenses,  and  both  parents  agree  to  assist  the  children  equally  with  their educational expenses and loans.

m) That the parties agree that the Plaintiff shall be entitled to claim the children for the tax credit in all tax years, on federal and state income tax returns. In the event that the tax dependency is reinstated, the Plaintiff shall receive the dependent income tax deduction for each child as set forth above, on all federal and state income tax returns.

## CONCLUSIONS OF LAW

- 1) That jurisdiction as required by Section 230 of the Domestic Relations Law has been satisfied.
- 2) That the Plaintiff is entitled to a Judgement of Divorce dissolving the marriage between the parties by reason of DRL §170(7) Relationship Irretrievably Broken.
- 3) That the conditions set forth in Section 253 of the Domestic Relations Law have been complied with.
- 4) That the Agreement of Settlement and Stipulation entered into between the parties on the 18th day of January, 2025, a copy of which is on file with the Court and incorporated herein by reference, shall survive and shall not be merged into the judgment, and the terms were fair and reasonable at the time of the making and the terms are not now unconscionable.
- 5) That the conditions set forth in Section 255 of the Domestic Relations Law have been complied with in that both parties have acknowledged in their agreement that they both fully understand that upon the entry of the Judgment of Divorce that he or she may no longer be allowed to receive health insurance coverage under his or her former spouses's health insurance plan and may be entitled to purchase health insurance on his or her own through a COBRA option, if available; and otherwise may be required to secure his or her own health insurance.
- 6) That the parties are self-supporting and capable of remaining so, and therefore neither party shall be required to pay maintenance.
- 7) That each party shall retain as his or her sole and separate property those items of property now in his or her possession and/or name, including but not limited to his or her real estate, business interests, automobiles, financial accounts, and any pension rights, 401k's and/or other retirement accounts that either party may possess, EXCEPT:
- i) That the Defendant shall transfer his interest in the marital residence commonly known as 242 Carriage Park, West Seneca, NY, via quitclaim deed, to the Plaintiff, at such time as the Plaintiff refinances and/or assumes the mortgage on the marital residence, and pays the Defendant seventy-nine thousand, seven-hundred and fifty dollars ($79,750.00). This amount represents the Defendant's half share of the equity in the marital residence.  The Plaintiff shall be responsible for paying all costs associated with the transfer of Defendant's interest. The Plaintiff shall be  responsible for paying all of the expenses associated with

home ownership  including but not limited to paying the mortgage, taxes, and  insurance, and shall indemnify, and hold Defendant harmless for said expenses, unless the Defendant is still residing at the marital residence, in that case, the expenses shall be split equally. ii) The Defendant agrees to transfer his interest in the 2016 Chevy Impala to Evelyn Fisher,

- and transfer his interest in the 2010 Ford Fusion to Coleton Fisher.
- iii)  Each party will retain as their sole and separate property fifty percent of the Joint savings account, after the Plaintiff first receives $3500.00, and the Defendant first receives $2500.00.
- iv) The parties agree to divide the household property as agreed and arranged.
- 8) That each party shall be responsible for those debts and obligations in his or her respective name, EXCEPT:
- i)  In the event that Plaintiff's student loans are not forgiven in July of 2025, the Defendant agrees to pay the Plaintiff twenty-five percent of the monthly payment on her student loans until such time as the loans are forgiven.
- 9) That each party shall be responsible for his or her own attorney's fees and disbursements.
- 10) That the Plaintiff shall be entitled to claim the children for the tax credit in all tax years, on federal and state income tax returns. In the event that the tax dependency is reinstated, the Plaintiff shall receive the dependent income tax deduction for each child as set forth above, on all federal and state income tax returns.
- 11) That the Plaintiff shall have the right to resume use of her maiden name or former surname, Bartella, should she so desire.
- 12) That the parties shall share joint legal custody of the one minor child, Evelyn Kay Fisher, and the Plaintiff shall be the primary residential and custodial parent of the child.
- 13) The Defendant shall pay Child Support to Plaintiff for the two (2) children, in the amount of no dollars

and no cents ($0.00), weekly; and that the parties have entered into an agreement that deviates from the basic child support obligation, and that the aforesaid obligation is not unjust or inappropriate for the reasons set forth in the agreement; specifically, that:

- a) The husband is expected to spend considerable time with the children.

- b) The husband is paying for half of the children's medical insurance.

- c) The husband is paying half of the children's expenses.

- 14) That the Defendant shall receive reasonable visitation with the one minor child, as agreed to by the parties, and upon reasonable notice to the Plaintiff.

- 15) That the Plaintiff shall provide medical and hospital insurance for the two (2) children on NYSHIP so long as it is available, and the Defendant will reimburse the Plaintiff half of the difference in the premium between a single plan and family plan.  Each party shall be responsible for paying half of all uninsured medical, dental, drug, optical, orthodontic, counseling and health related expenses incurred on behalf of the children.

- 16) Both parties shall pay half of the children's expenses as agreed and arranged until the children reach the age of 21, including but not limited to their respective cell phones, car insurance, and other necessary expenses, and both parents agree to assist the children equally with their educational expenses and loans.

## COMPLAINT IN INTERPLEADER

Plaintiff, Bankers Conseco Life Insurance Company, by counsel, pursuant to NYCPLR § 1006, for its Complaint in Interpleader alleges as follows:

## PARTIES

- 1. Bankers Conseco Life Insurance Company ("Bankers") is an insurance company organized  and  existing  under  the  laws  of the  State  of New  York  with  its  principal  place  of business in Hamilton County, Indiana.  Bankers is  duly authorized to  do  business in the  State of New York.
- 2. Upon information and belief, Karla Warren ("Warren")  is  a resident of Buffalo, Erie County, New York.
- 3. Upon  information and belief, Kimberly Hemphill, a/k/a Kimberly Garner ("Hemphill") is a resident of  Buffalo, Erie County, New York.

## VENUE

- 4. Venue  is  proper  as  designated  by  Plaintiff  in  this  County  pursuant  to  CPLR §503(a) in that at least one the Defendants resides in this County.

## CAUSE OF ACTION IN INTERPLEADER

- 5. On December 6, 2010, Bankers issued to the Debra Warren (the "Insured"), a Whole Life  Policy with a  face  value  of $8,000  as  Policy Number  ***5818  (the  "Policy").  A  true  and accurate copy of  the Policy, including the Application, is attached hereto as Exhibit 1 1 ·
- 6. In  the  Application  for  the  Policy,  the  Insured  named  her  daughter,  Warren,  as  the primary  beneficiary  of  the Policy  proceeds, and  her daughter, Tanisha  Simmons  as  the contingent beneficiary.
- 7. On August 12, 2015, the Insured purportedly executed a change of beneficiary form relating to the Policy and designated Hemphill as primary beneficiary of  the Policy proceeds, and Tanisha Simmons as the contingent beneficiary.  Bankers confirmed such change of beneficiary by letter dated August 26,  2015.  True  and accurate  copies  of the August  12th  change form  and Bankers' August 26th letter are collectively attached hereto as Exhibit 2.
- 8. On June  7,  2016,  Warren,  through  counsel,  notified  Bankers  that  the  Insured  had passed away on June 4,  2016, and expressed concern that the Insured may be been "threatened, coerced and harassed [sic]" to  change the beneficiary of the Policy, as  she "labored under some very  serious  health  issues  ... and  had  been  diagnosed  with  moderate  intellectual  disability." Bankers was requested to  conduct an investigation and refrain from making any disbursements under  the  Policy.  A  true  and  accurate  copy  of Warren's attorney's June J1h letter  is  attached hereto as Exhibit 3.
- 9. The Policy was paid up and in full force and effect at the time of  the Insured's  death.
- death. 10. Upon information and belief, no  probate  estate  was  opened following the Insured's

Exhibits are redacted for HIP  AA and privacy reasons.

- 11. On  July  12,  2016,  Hemphill  requested  from  Bankers  "an  update  form  proving  I am the  Beneficiary  Policy  Holder of Debra Warren."  A  true  and  accurate  copy  of Hemphill's July 12th request is attached hereto as Exhibit 4.
- 12. By letter  dated  August  1,  2016,  Warren  restated  her  concern that  the  Insured  had been coerced into changing the beneficiary of  the Policy, and provided a letter from a health care provider stating the Insured had been diagnosed with Mild Mental Retardation on March 3, 2008. Warren also submitted a written claim to Bankers seeking payment of the Policy proceeds. True and  accurate  copies  of Warren's August  1st  correspondence  and  accompanying  documents  are collectively attached hereto as Exhibit 5.
- 13. By letters  dated August 29,  2016, Bankers  advised Warren and  Hemphill of the completing claims to the Policy proceeds, and requested that they attempt to reach an agreement as  to  the  disposition  of same.  True  and  accurate  copies  of Bankers'  August 29th letters  are collectively attached hereto as Exhibit 6.
- 14. By  letter  dated September  1, 2016, Warren  advised  Bankers  that  she  was interested  in reaching  an  agreement with Hemphill  as  to  distribution of the  Policy proceeds.  A true and accurate copy of  Warren's September 1st letter is attached hereto as Exhibit 7.
- 15. On October 12, 2016, Hemphill phoned Bankers and stated that she did not want to come to an agreement with Warren as to distribution of  the Policy proceeds.
- 16. Bankers  cannot  determine  to  whom  the  disputed  Policy  proceeds  belongs  and fears exposure to multiple liability if  it delivers the Policy proceeds to either of  the Defendants.
- 17. Bankers claims no interest in the Policy proceeds and wishes to deposit it in Court and  be  discharged  from  any  obligation  for  any  of the  Policy  proceeds,  interest  thereon,  the detention of such, or further liability to either of  the Defendants after the date of  deposit.

- 18. Bankers  stands  ready  to  deposit  with  the  Clerk  of this  Court  the  sum  of Eight Thousand  Dollars  ($8,000.00),  plus  interest  as  provided  by  law,  which  represents  the  Policy proceeds,  being the  face  value  Policy,  plus  additional  interest,  if any,  as  allowed by applicable law to the date of  deposit with the Court.
- 19. Bankers has incurred, is  incurring, and will continue to  incur costs and attorneys fees in bringing this action.

WHEREFORE, Bankers prays for judgment as follows:

- 1. That Defendants and each of them be ordered to  interplead and litigate their claims to  the  Policy  proceeds  in  this  Court,  and  be  enjoined  from  commencing  any  other  action  or proceeding against Bankers related to the Policy;
- 2. That  Bankers,  its  agents,  employees,  representatives,  predecessors,  successors,  and assigns be  discharged from  and against any liability,  suits,  debts, judgments, dues,  sums and/or causes  of action whether at  law or at equity, to  either of the  Defendants,  and/or to  any  person, entity, claimant, defendant for benefits arising under and pursuant to the Policy on account of  the death of  the Insured;
- 3. That the Defendants, and each of  them, be permanently restrained and enjoined from instituting  and  prosecuting  a  suit,  civil  action  or  civil  proceeding  in  any  state,  federal  or  other court  of competent jurisdiction  against  Bankers  in order to  seek  benefits  or  in  order  to  assert damage claims arising under the Policy as a consequence of  the death of  the Insured;
- 4. That Bankers  be  awarded  costs  and  reasonable  attorney  fees  incurred to  prosecute this action; and,
- 5. That Bankers be awarded all other and further relief as the Court may deem proper.
